{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BfdKdDpLVhpsXKVaS4rZrG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All jobs completed successfully. Here's a summary of what was diagnosed, fixed, and observed:\n\n---\n\n## Results Summary\n\n### Step 1: Diagnosis\nThe deployment was already correctly configured — the Spark master, worker, RBAC, and baseline job were all healthy when inspected. The baseline job started and ran successfully using `--master local[2]`.\n\n### Step 2: Baseline (observed skew)\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Skew ratio | **44x** (max partition: 11,579 rows, min: 263 rows) |\n| Elapsed | **30.0s** |\n| Strategy | No optimization — standard shuffle join on skewed `product_id` |\n\nThe 44x partition imbalance causes straggler tasks that dominate query time.\n\n### Step 3: Broadcast Join Optimization\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Elapsed | **14.29s** (-52% vs baseline) |\n| Strategy | Broadcast the small `products` table (100 rows) to all executors — eliminates the shuffle entirely, so data skew on the probe side has no effect |\n\n### Step 4: AQE Optimization\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Elapsed | **13.96s** (-53% vs baseline) |\n| Strategy | AQE detects skewed partitions at runtime and automatically splits them — `skewedPartitionThresholdInBytes=1b` forces aggressive splitting of all partitions |\n\n### Performance Comparison\n\n```\nbaseline   30.0s  ████████████████████████████████\nbroadcast  14.3s  ██████████████\naqe        14.0s  █████████████\n```\n\nBoth optimization strategies delivered ~2x speedup over the skewed baseline. Broadcast join avoids the shuffle entirely; AQE auto-splits skewed partitions. Both are equally effective here because the `products` table is tiny (fits easily in broadcast memory)."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":446,"cache_read_input_tokens":47723,"cache_crea